</mj-text>
    <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>The what</strong>: Jimmy Lai, the 78-year-old founder of Apple Daily, has been sentenced to <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2026/02/08/china/jimmy-lai-sentenced-20-years-intl-hnk" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d; color: black;">20 years in prison</a> under Beijing‚Äôs National Security Law. Lai was convicted on two national security charges and one sedition count. The court cited his activism, Apple Daily‚Äôs editorial stance, and lobbying of US officials as efforts to invite foreign pressure on Beijing and Hong Kong.</p>
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>The reaction:</strong> The ruling delays parole eligibility until his late 90s, effectively making the sentence a life term, given his health. Rights groups and Western governments condemned the sentence as a grave blow to press freedom. Amnesty International called it a ‚Äúcold-blooded attack‚Äù on free expression. Human Rights Watch warned that the prison conditions make the punishment life-threatening. Britain and the EU labeled the case politically motivated.</p>
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>What‚Äôs next?</strong> Supporters are urging President Trump to raise Lai‚Äôs case with President Xi Jinping during the anticipated US-China talks. Lai can appeal, but acquittals under the National Security Law are rare, and the process is slow, making the sentence likely to stand. His sentencing highlights how Hong Kong has changed since 2020, with dissidents jailed, civil society restricted, and critical media shut down.</p>
</mj-text>
