    <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>Summary: Rising tensions between Ethiopia and Eritrea revive fears of a border war, threatening stability in the Horn of Africa. </strong></p>
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>The what</strong>: Ethiopia has accused Eritrea of sending soldiers into its territory and helping rebel groups. Ethiopia called this "outright aggression," alleging that Eritrean troops were conducting joint military manoeuvres with Ethiopian rebel groups. <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cn87lzrj1l7o" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d; color: black;">Eritrea denied the accusation</a>, saying it is false and part of a hostile political campaign. This argument raises concerns about a possible conflict between the two countries.</p>
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>The background:</strong> Eritrea and Ethiopia fought a brutal border war from 1998 to 2000 that left more than 100,000 people dead. Relations thawed in 2018 when Ethiopian PM Abiy Ahmed signed a peace agreement with Eritrea. The two later became allies during <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-54964378" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d; color: black;">Ethiopia‚Äôs civil war in Tigray</a> from 2020 to 2022, with Eritrea backing Ethiopian government forces. That alliance has since unravelled, with Ethiopia now accusing Eritrea of supporting Tigrayan factions that oppose the peace agreement.</p>
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>The big picture: </strong>The escalating dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea underscores the fragility of peace in the Horn of Africa. Ethiopia‚Äôs drive for access to the Red Sea, which it describes as an existential necessity, directly clashes with Eritrea‚Äôs concerns over sovereignty and national security. Any escalation risks destabilising an already fragile region, threatening Ethiopia‚Äôs internal peace process and wider Red Sea security.</p>
</mj-text>
