<mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>The brotherhood:</strong> Turkey and Azerbaijan <a href="https://www.geojuristoday.in/post/brotherhood-discourse-of-turkey-azerbaijan-and-pakistan-an-analysis" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d; color: black;">share a strong bond</a> for numerous reasons. They are both of Turkic origin and share many elements, including history, culture, language, and geopolitical interests, that connect them. This unity is summed up in the phrase, "One nation, two states." Turkey was the first country to recognize Azerbaijan‚Äôs statehood.</p>
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>Foreign policy goals: </strong>This relationship is rooted in pan-Turkism, a strategy aimed at countering Western hegemony. Azerbaijan sits at a strategic crossroads between Russia, Iran, and the Caspian Sea, while Turkey is a NATO power bridging Europe and Asia. By working together, they counterbalance Armenia and major regional players like Russia and Iran. Their partnership has deepened through mutual support, especially during Azerbaijan‚Äôs conflict with Armenia over Nagorno-Karabakh. Turkey provided military and diplomatic backing. Armenia and Turkey also hold long standing grievences that are over a century old.</p>
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0 0 10px 0;"><strong>On the ground:</strong> Economically, these two countries are inseparable; they collaborate closely in energy, trade, and infrastructure. Turkey supports initiatives to improve infrastructure, increase prosperity, unlock energy and trade routes, and strengthen regional connectivity. Presidents Recep Tayyip Erdoƒüan and Ilham Aliyev embrace nationalist narratives and view their partnership as a means to strengthen domestic support and political legitimacy.</p>
